                      votes <span class="ItemCaption">Reviewed: </span>
                      <span>2005-04-16</span>
                    </div>
                    <span>My Favorite of Burroughs and by far the most accessible of his work that is hilarious and haunting it is hard to imagine someone writing crazy stuff back then. Keith Richards wasn't even born then but others primarily American artists were apparently struggling with the junk sickness. Despite our apparent vapid state in the eyes of the world we have held on to a certain underworld. Not so much that Junk was the only thing but the art that came along with it as like a tsunami for the later waves of British influence. It is ironic how the people of America often feel inadequate to their European counterparts - Even Canada! When we really look at things it becomes clear how the invasions are going in many directions. Neil got by on his charisma alone and he was not much of a roommate, so I have been told. This book is one of the mother loads for sure and a good lead into the deeper stuff of Burroughs and many of his contemporary. I loved the fight with the cat perhaps most of all. 
